title: Want To Buy:  Looking for Curio / Relic Firearms pistols shotguns rifles older or newer
postcontent:
I am a collector; I enjoy finding, collecting, and in some cases restoring antique, curio, and relic fires (but will look at anything). My offer for your firearm will be more than you will get at a Pawn Shop, trade in at a dealer, or what you will get at a gun show. If you need to sell today I can buy today. 

Always keep in mind this is a business transaction, don't take it personal if we don't agree on your items condition or price. A lot of it is subjective, so if we can't agree it's okay. We all have our opinions. You may have sentimental value for your firearm, could have been a family members etc... I respect that, however unless the family member was famous and it adds some provenance to the firearm, it is not something I can pay extra for. 

I determine the current market value of a firearm using the NRA grading standard, book value and the selling price on the major auction sites. This gives me the current market value of a firearm either NIB or NRA Excellent. What people are asking and what items sell for can be very different. Taking in consideration the gun(s) you are selling are not new, and may have been fired, also whether or not you have the factory boxes, and manuals along with any accessories. I come up with an offer. For optics, unless they are an intrinsic part of the model, I price them separate from the rifles using the same method. If I can buy it now, in an auction, for less than you are asking, then why would I buy it from you? Boxes and Manuals are always a plus.

My offers are subject to inspection. Initial offers are based on an assumption of a grade of NRA Good to Excellent. If I find any blemishes or condition issues upon inspection that have not been previously discussed it will affect the offer. My offer is good for 30 days.

I also buy surplus ammo

Once we agree to a price I will be happy to purchase your firearm, I will provide you with a bill of sale, a copy for you and a copy for me. This is to protect both of us. The bill of sale will have to have the Make, Model, and Serial number of the firearm, along with your Name, DOB, and TDL #. You must be at least 21 years old to sell a sidearm, and 18 years old to sell a rifle or shotgun in Texas. The sale is private party to private party. If you agree to the terms and price we can do business.

title: For Sale:  Colt AR6720 Lightweight LE Carbine 5.56 20 Rd NIB
postcontent:
The AR6720 represents a new generation of Colt rifle, which comes standard with an optics ready rail and a flip-up rear iron sight.

Colt’s use of the MaTech flip-up sight is unique among flip-up rear sights in that it has adjustment for both Windage and elevation and its slender design allows for maximum peripheral vision when in use giving the shooter the most un-obscured view of the target. These are also the reasons that the MaTech flip up rear sight has been the US Military standard for almost a decade.

Designed specifically for the Law Enforcement officer, its lighter platform recognizes the need to minimize weight while not compromising durability as firearms are generally carried for long periods of time and weight becomes a significant factor.

The 16” standard weight barrel is magnetic particle tested after proofing by Colt to ensure every barrel is made of perfect steel with zero flaws. Because of this tight quality control, Colt barrels are durable enough to handle thousands of rounds of highly accurate semi-auto fire yet maintain a lightweight profile. Its 1:7 twist gives it the flexibility to use the widest range of ammunition from 40 grain varmint rounds to 77 grain long range match, while maintaining ballistic stability.

The bolt head is also magnetic particle tested by Colt to ensure all steel surrounding the cartridge is perfect and without flaw. These extra steps of quality are what set Colt rifles apart from other AR-15 type clones.

The AR6720 is a hybrid of Colt’s Government Carbine model AR6520 and Colt’s Flagship M4 Carbine model LE6920. This Lightweight Law Enforcement Carbine has a roll mark of AR-15A4- recognizing Colt’s newest designation of an ORC (optics ready carbine).

Our dimensional tolerances are held so close that you will never encounter a Wilson magazine that doesn't drop free from your pistol or that your rounds are tight inside the tube as long as your pistol and ammo are close to proper specifications. 

"Back in 1980, Bill Wilson asked me to test some of his new Wilson-Rogers .45 magazines. He explained that he felt they had solved the problem of cracked feed lips and that their new magazines fed much more reliably than any others on the market. Well, it's 30 years later now and I'm still using some of those original 6 prototype magazines that Bill sent me… Through the years they have proven without a doubt to be the most reliable and durable 1911 magazines on the market. I have personally used specimens from various production runs through the years and have yet to see any quality variation or have one let me down in any way. They are my first and only choice as well as the choice of the elite special forces units I train. I trust my life to a Wilson Combat® pistol and 8-round Wilson magazines; so can you…"
Ken Hackathorn- Tactical Shooting Instructor, Gun Writer, IPSC & IDPA Founder
